    "content": "**Geopolitiks Snacks** - May 10, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🕊️ The three-day Ukraine truce lasted exactly like expected\n\nThe ceasefire arrived with a prisoner-swap headline and immediately began collecting footnotes.\n\n- **The deal:** AP says Trump announced a May 9-11 ceasefire and a 1,000-for-1,000 prisoner exchange, with Putin adviser Yuri Ushakov and Zelenskyy confirming acceptance.\n- **The unraveling:** by Sunday, Russia accused Ukraine of more than 1,000 violations; Ukrainian officials reported Russian drone and artillery strikes that killed one person and injured others.\n- **The symbolism:** Zelenskyy said freeing prisoners mattered more than Red Square, while formally keeping the parade area off Ukraine's target list.\n\n*Peace process speedrun: announcement, parade optics, mutual accusations, repeat.*\n\n**Sources:** [AP](https://apnews.com/article/007c385a9b81ba81b4b51c1a5b8ace9b) | [AP](https://apnews.com/article/beabe2b017b868e99408e227c403789b)\n\n---\n\n## 🛢️ The Gulf ceasefire now includes drones over everyone\n\nThe U.S.-Iran truce is still alive, provided one defines alive as actively needing air defenses.\n\n- **The Sunday test:** AP says a drone set a small fire on a commercial ship northeast of Doha, while the UAE shot down two drones and blamed Iran.\n- **The spillover:** Kuwait said hostile drones entered its airspace early Sunday; Qatar said the targeted ship was coming from Abu Dhabi into a southern port.\n- **The backdrop:** the pause already had Iran restricting Hormuz traffic and the U.S. enforcing a blockade of Iranian ports.\n\n*Ceasefires are more convincing when three Gulf states are not filing drone reports before breakfast.*\n\n**Sources:** [AP](https://apnews.com/article/f8812db41837336d816efaea7bc1c44a) | [AP](https://apnews.com/article/6490db55a65880a61a6233eff7acc68b)\n\n---\n\n## 📵 Iran turned the internet into a rationed privilege\n\nTehran has found a brutal way to simplify online life: remove the online part for nearly everyone.\n\n- **The duration:** Iran International, citing NetBlocks, said the nationwide blackout entered its 69th day on May 7 after 1,632 hours of severe disruption to international connectivity.\n- **The scale:** The Guardian reported monitors called it the longest national-scale blackout since the Arab Spring, beginning after U.S.-Israel strikes in late February.\n- **The control layer:** reports describe tiered access for selected users, VPN restrictions and pressure on satellite terminals.\n\n*Authoritarian resilience now comes bundled with offline mode and a very selective whitelist.*\n\n**Sources:** [Iran International](https://www.iranintl.com/en/202605078364) | [The Guardian](https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2026/apr/06/iran-internet-blackout-is-longest-national-shutdown-since-arab-spring)\n"
  }
]
